===Etymology===
From {{etyl|enm|en}}, from {{etyl|fro|en}} {{term|fable|lang=fro}}, from {{etyl|la|en}} {{term|fabula|lang=la}}, from {{term|fari|fā(rī)|to speak, say|lang=la}} + {{term|bula||instrumental suffix|lang=la}}. See {{term|Ban}}, and compare {{term|fabulous|lang=en}}, {{term|fame|lang=en}}.

===Pronunciation===
* {{audio|en-us-fable.ogg|Audio (US)|lang=en}}
* {{rhymes|eɪbəl|lang=en}}

===Noun===
{{en-noun}}

# A [[fictitious]] [[narrative]] intended to [[enforce]] some useful [[truth]] or [[precept]], usually with [[animals]], [[birds]] etc as [[characters]]; an [[apologue]]. Prototypically, [[w:Aesop's Fables|Aesop's Fables]].
# Any story told to excite wonder; common talk; the [[theme]] of talk.
#* [[w:First Epistle to Timothy|1 Timothy]] 4:7,
#*: Old wives' '''fables'''.
#* [[w:Alfred Tennyson, 1st Baron Tennyson|Alfred Tennyson]],
#*: We grew / The '''fable''' of the city where we dwelt.
# [[fiction|Fiction]]; [[untruth]]; falsehood.
#* [[w:Joseph Addison|Joseph Addison]],
#*: It would look like a '''fable''' to report that this gentleman gives away a great fortune by secret methods.
# The plot, story, or connected series of events forming the subject of an epic or dramatic poem.
#* Dryden
#*: The moral is the first business of the poet; this being formed, he contrives such a design or '''fable''' as may be most suitable to the moral.

